After hearing that Ellen Yin's hospitality group was up for a James Beard award, we pushed a. kitchen up in our list! We easily made reservations for a Thursday night, arriving a touch early but being seated without issue. The entry was a little confusing since you walk through a large foyer of what looks like a hotel to get to the restaurant; there were signs, but we weren't expecting that lead in. The space is pretty large, with ample bar seating but plenty of tables and booths as well. The dim lighting paired with tea lights and the accompanying modern furniture made for a fun ambience. 

For food and drink ... we were intrigued by the wine list, specifically the natural wines, but we didn't want to commit to a full bottle (natty wines unavailable by the glass). We instead both opted for cocktails; each featured fun, unique ingredients and were refreshing (names of cocktails we ordered are escaping me!). For eats, based on Yelp reviews and Chef Mike Solmonolov's recs, my husband ordered the burger and I went for the octopus "lyonnaise". My husband spoke highly of the burger, deeming it one of the finest in Philly - he particularly loved the cornichon and dijon additions! My dish was very unique - the salty trout roe paired nicely with the fatty bacon, but I felt like I was being *somewhat* healthy with it being atop lettuce. I wasn't expecting to be all that full afterwards, but I was pleasantly surprised! Since we skipped out on an app (and Yelp spoke wonders of the chocolate tahini cake), we opted in for dessert. Originally planning on both ordering the cake, our server convinced us to get one cake and one panna cotta, and we're glad we did! The cake was excellent - incredibly rich and decadent with the sweetness nicely paired with the creamy tahini. The panna cotta was the flip side of this - very light and creamy, a satisfying but not overwhelming end to our meal.  

Overall, we enjoyed our dinner at a. kitchen! Ambience was great, service was quick, and food was solid. Price point was a little high, but not aggressively so. I would definitely make it back to try other cocktails and the wine list, as well as work my way through the apps and other menu options. James Beard gave it accolades for a reason! Thanks for a fun date night, a. kitchen!

I found this restaurant as a semi finalist for James Beard Outstanding Restaurateur (Ellen Yin of High Street Hospitality Group, which includes Fork, A.kitchen + Bar, High Street Philly, and others). I'm thinking I may have caught the restaurant on an off day. It was slow weekday. 

A bit disappointed by the food. The fried mushrooms were a bit dry even with the aioli sauce. It felt like every last drop of moisture from the mushroom was wrung dry. I also ordered the octopus dish with thick bacon and salmon roe eggs atop soft boiled eggs and a bed of salad. It was a decent dish. I found an eggshell and nicely mentioned it and they were very nice about it and apologized and removed it from my bill. 

Of course I fully tipped on the full bill and they deserved it because the service was excellent throughout. Spent time walking through the menu and giving suggestions and advice. I just found this to be a bit disappointing food wise since it came short of my expectation. I do think I'll give the other restaurants a try or come by and see if it was just an off day. Also it's known for its selection of natural wines so next time I'll get a glass too.

Great food and great service. It's no wonder A.Kitchen won a James Beard award! The ambiance was intimate, perfect for a date night! The food was so flavorful and so delicious. Can't remember the truffle/lamb/potato dish but this was the best ever. Portion sizes were perfect for my party of 2. Highly recommend!

Lovely location with a warm, cozy dim-lit dinner vibe inside. Service was super friendly and attentive with water and new utensils/plates. 

I came here last night with my husband after winning a $100 gift card in a raffle, and we had really fantastic tasting food.  Truly, every meal was delicious and there was absolutely nothing negative to say about any of it. As odd as it sounds and as great as it was, we didn't like the limited menu options here. We found ourselves struggling at first then just ordering a little bit of everything. If I didn't win a gift card and was browsing Yelp for a Philly restaurant, the menu alone here would not draw me in. In terms of my favorite, the burger was outstanding and for me, the finisher was the chocolate caramel tahini cake.

The kitchen was so accommodating for vegans and we had the most amazing time on our engagement anniversary. The cocktails were on point and the beet salad was definitely the star of the experience. 

Highly recommend this place for your special occasion.

Finally returned to a.kitchen. Much better experience than many years prior. Although we found the menu to be limited for our pescatarian/celiac diner and had to get creative with ordering multiple tuna appetizers as an entree, the remainder of the group enjoyed their meal. The Cheeseburger (cornichon, american cheese, dijonnaise, high street sesame roll) was well-seasoned--loved the cornichon flavor, which was highly prevalent!

There was some miscommunication about the request for bread, which had to be repeated, but overall service was pleasant.

While the space has cozy décor, it becomes quite loud/difficult to converse in when full. Would love to see more non-alcoholic beverage options on the drinks list.

Excellent starters. Raw scallops were inventive. Raw peaches salad was on-point. Fry bread was hearty and delicious. Great tequila forward rhinestone cowboy cocktail too. And service was strong- waitress was knowledgeable and had excellent recommendations and fun anecdotes to share about the menu

Only dings we're that the octopus main was good but not great. And dessert menu was meager with only two meh options so we got ice cream down the block instead 

Strong dinner overall

I thought a.kitchen was ok pre-COVID. I've been back a few times recently--my first visits since the pandemic--and I was impressed. The bartender on the nights that I went there made excellent drinks, the entire staff was friendly, and all of the dishes were really, really good. Given its location's popularity, it can get crowded quickly, even after a momentary lull (just something to be aware of). And while this hasn't been a problem for me yet (knock on wood), you never know if fellow Rittenhouse diners will be pleasant to be around or annoyingly entitled and pretentious (the latter is why I avoid a few nearby establishments). As long as a.kitchen continues to deliver, I'll be a regular.

First timer here and really enjoyed dining here.  The ambiance is very nice - dim light but not too dark.  The food there was very good - good for sharing a few dishes.  I particularly enjoyed the gougères and the bavette steak.  Flavors as well as cooking was very good.  The gnocchi dish was a bit on the heavier side but also very good.
For dessert, the chocolate tahini cake was great.
Service was also good - waitress was very pleasant.

We stopped here for a drink before our dinner reservations somewhere else. When I walked to the bathroom I noticed that the food on the plates looked amazing. I told my wife and we decided to stay. I quickly looked up reviews and saw they weren't great, but decided to trust my gut (we know good restaurants). Thank god I stayed, this place is incredible. It is a foodie paradise. Seems people were leaving dumb reviews for not having a fork or spoon, for example. Everything we ordered was delectable, the cocktails were divine, and the bartender who served us (Jess) was fantastic. I highly recommend a.kitchen for anyone traveling to Philly. The vibe was awesome. Hope to come back some day!

I definitely had a hard time reviewing this restaurant since I really wanted to enjoy it. The location is wonderful and we found seats outside right in the shade. The service was a little spotty, I'm not sure if they were short staffed but our waiter seem to be covering most of the restaurant. We tried the best salad, an omelette and a side of the gougères. We had never heard of gougères before, but we saw another table eating them and had to try them -- they were delicious! The French omelette was a bit under for me and the beat salad was okay, but nothing really memorable. I'm not sure if I just ordered the wrong things or should have tried out their dinner menu, but I think I'd try this again for dinner or happy hour.

Excellent food. A nice balance of flavors, and none are too strong or too weak. We have had the beet salad twice and it was very tasty. The servers were very accommodating for our desire to eat sharing all the food.

Today, Friday, November 6th, I had the pleasure of visiting this restaurant. We had a reservation at 4:30 PM (not the busiest time). The food was excellent, probably the best oysters I've had in a long time and I am an "oyster" person. However, I will never visit this establishment again:
1. The oysters arrive without an oyster fork (not a big deal, but not everyone wants to dig in with a big one).
2. The dish that had a soup base came without a spoon ( not a big deal, we can always ask). 
The waiter was a pleasant person, but I wanted to share my advice (the restaurant is in need of basic service training) and I asked for the manager. 
And here, we have a  winner. This person's look and behavior were saying one thing: "just, please!!!!, go away, because the food is good, right?"
Yes, and he can have it all to himself now. 
Best, Wishes,
Elena.

5/5 ambiance. So cute inside and outside! I loved especislly the indoor seating because you can see the bartender and the chef. There is also a wall of alcoholic bottles under night lights which is really pretty!

5/5 service. Our waiter was super friendly and happy to serve us. He was very attentive as well!

5/5 food. I highly recommend the OCTOPUS 'LYONNAISE' and GRASS FED BEEF TARTARE!! The beef tartare is more on the refreshing side, and unlike any other beef tartares that I had. The brunch menu is a bit limited and pretty simple for the price, but the potatoes are AMAZING!

Highly recommend the mushroom bolognese and the chicken parfait. The shukshuka was a little too tomato-y for my tastes (shocker, I know) 

The drinks were strong, the way we like it. Service was great, the waiter was attentive and patient with us as we got carried away with conversation and forgot to look at the menu for the first 20 minutes. Don't worry, we did order drinks as soon as we sat down. Priorities. 

Highly recommend the outdoor setting al fresco. They have a cute covered area with seating arrangements for parties of two or four. Can't speak about how crowded it gets during peak hours but we went for brunch on a Sunday at 11 am and there were spaces between us and the other parties.
My favorite burger place in Philadelphia, and I am gluten free and don't even eat the bun. The restaurant has a nice vibe as well!

Love this place. The food is great. Unique dishes, fresh menus. Cocktails are out of this world. Eat in the restaurant but order cocktails from the bar - they're exceptional. Excellent service every time I've been there. 
The bar is a nice place to hang out with friends. The kitchen is always busy but you can have a quiet dinner and conversation. Sometime, I'd love to sit by the open kitchen to watch the staff in action.
The service and ambiance is amazing for a not too pricey elevated week night experience. Great wine. Great food. Great staff!
Only had drinks but their service was good and the drinks were even better. Recommend for cocktail hour.

We sat at the Chef's table and had a great experience watching Chefs do their thing! Waiter was very knowledgeable and gave great suggestions... sampled some new wines too.  Orange wine is a new obsession...
